<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="41" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,359,1069]" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,684,709]" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blainville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[322,444,684,709]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinometridae" genus="Echinometra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mathaei">
<emphasis box="[322,444,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">E. mathaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from the other 
<collectingRegion box="[858,891,684,709]" country="United Kingdom" name="Surrey" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">Sri</collectingRegion>
Lankan echinometrids, except from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blainville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[1305,1429,684,709]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinometridae" genus="Echinometra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="oblonga">
<emphasis box="[1305,1322,685,708]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1337,1429,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">oblonga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in having the test elongated through the axis between ambulacrum I and interambulacrum 3, and only four pore pairs in the pore arcs of the ambulacra.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,359,1069]" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blainville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[199,319,791,816]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinometridae" genus="Echinometra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mathaei">
<emphasis box="[199,319,791,816]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">E. mathaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blainville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[373,496,791,816]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinometridae" genus="Echinometra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="oblonga">
<emphasis box="[373,496,791,816]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">E. oblonga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cannot be easily distinguished from each other. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[1034,1306,791,816]" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" refId="ref10602" refString="Mortensen, T. (1943 b) A Monograph of the Echinoidea III. 3, Camarodonta. II. Echinidae, Strongylocentrotidae, Parasaleniidae, Echinometridae. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 446 pp." type="book" year="1943">Mortensen (1943b: 394)</bibRefCitation>
admits that “there are no reliable characters in the test distinguishing 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blainville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[820,912,828,853]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinometridae" genus="Echinometra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="oblonga">
<emphasis box="[820,912,828,853]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">oblonga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the typical 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blainville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[1116,1206,828,853]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinometridae" genus="Echinometra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mathaei">
<emphasis box="[1116,1206,828,853]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">mathaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”. Hence, molecular analyses are required to distinguish these species unequivocally, although sperm morphology and spicules have been shown to be very useful in distinguishing some members of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blainville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[945,1067,900,925]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinometridae" genus="Echinometra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mathaei">
<emphasis box="[945,1067,900,925]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">E. mathaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species complex (Arakaki 
<emphasis box="[1378,1436,900,925]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">et al.</emphasis>
1998; Bronstein &amp; Loya 2013).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,359,1069]" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">
Two colour variants, green and brown, occur in 
<collectingCountry box="[768,886,972,997]" name="Sri Lanka" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">Sri Lanka</collectingCountry>
. There is a high likelihood that more than one species is present on the island, pending full molecular analyses of additional specimens from across the range of echinometrids currently listed under the names 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blainville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[683,805,1044,1069]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinometridae" genus="Echinometra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="mathaei">
<emphasis box="[683,805,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">E. mathaei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Blainville" baseAuthorityYear="1825" box="[858,982,1044,1069]" class="Echinoidea" family="Echinometridae" genus="Echinometra" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Camarodonta" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="oblonga">
<emphasis box="[858,982,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="41">E. oblonga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
